properties.Title: Wind Effect Alert Issued For The South Basins Of Lake Manitoba And Lake Winnipeg.
properties.Summary:
Description: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a high wind-effect warning for the south shore of the south basin of Lake Manitoba, and for the shorelines near Gimli on the west side and Victoria Beach on the east side of Lake Winnipeg. High winds are forecast to develop this evening and are expected to last until Thursday morning, June 11, 2020. Wind speed and wave action could raise water levels as much as five feet or more. Be watchful as these winds can result in significant and forceful wave action on shorelines. Property owners in the affected area should take all necessary precautions to stay safe.
Expires: 2020-06-11T12:00:00-05:00

Area: South shore of south basin of Lake Manitoba, and for the shorelines near Gimli on the west side and Victoria Beach on the east side of Lake Winnipeg.

properties.Title: Update: Flood Warning Issued For Southeastern Manitoba
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a flood warning for southeastern Manitoba due to continued rise in water levels along rivers and creeks in this area. Significant overland flooding is also occurring. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur or occurring. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Use caution when driving on all roads, as road conditions may have changed. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions issued by local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca Follow @MBGov and @MBGovRoads on Twitter or stay tuned to local media.

properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Conditions are favourable for the development of severe thunderstorms that may be capable of producing strong wind gusts. Thunderstorms have developed over Southwestern Ontario early this morning. These thunderstorms may be accompanied by wind gusts of 90 km/h. Small hail is also possible with these thunderstorms. These thunderstorms will move northeastward and out of the area early this morning. ### Strong wind gusts can toss loose objects, damage weak buildings, break branches off trees and overturn large vehicles. Locally heavy rain is also possible. Severe thunderstorm watches are issued when atmospheric conditions are favourable for the development of thunderstorms that could produce one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm. properties.Title: Heat Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heat event continues through Wednesday. Temperatures tonight will remain in the low twenties, especially in urban areas, providing little relief from the heat. One more hot day with afternoon temperatures in the low thirties is expected Wednesday. Humidex values in the upper thirties to near 40 are expected Wednesday in this tropical air mass. Hot and humid air can also bring deteriorating air quality and can result in the Air Quality Health Index to approach the high risk category. A cold front accompanied by showers and thunderstorms will move through Southern Ontario Wednesday night, bringing this heat event to an end. ### Extreme heat affects everyone. The risks are greater for young children, pregnant women, older adults, people with chronic illnesses and people working or exercising outdoors. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Conditions are favourable for the development of dangerous thunderstorms that may be capable of producing damaging wind gusts, large hail and heavy rain. Thunderstorms moving through the region this evening may produce torrential downpours local rainfall amounts of 50 mm in an hour or less. There is also potential for locally higher rainfall amounts tonight of 50 to 100 mm over areas that get two or more thunderstorms in a row. Wind gusts to 90 km/h are also possible this evening. ### Very strong wind gusts can damage buildings, down trees and blow large vehicles off the road. Intense lightning is likely with any thunderstorm that develops. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm. For more information: http://www.emergencymanagementontario.ca/english/beprepared/beprepared.html.
